yKEBsOXCp5HTEUAnuenDL9Tx6ySDlTBFUHsDY0YeIX4eROw4LH0uK0VadOdxhod26sRsY8b\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring Java version checks**\\n\\nI'm considering using `Runtime.version().feature()` to check if it's 24 or higher, since no reflection would be involved. If the JDK version is 24+, I assume the class exists, and I could test that with `ProcessInfo.VirtualThreadsInfo`. The problem seems to be around hardcoding JDK versions and their features compared to artifact versions. I might opt for `ClassUtils.isPresent`, which tests for class presence, but it still involves indirect reflection, which I'm trying to avoid. It's a bit tangled!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering native image effects**\\n\\nI'm thinking about how using `ClassUtils.isPresent` might be impacted in a native image context, particularly if the metadata is absent. This could potentially create issues since the presence of JDK classes would normally be fine, but in a native image, things might be different. It raises the question of reliability, and I want to make sure I'm accounting for how these changes could affect the overall functionality. It's something I need to keep an eye on!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering code initialization**\\n\\nI'm thinking of initializing the scheduler using Thread.startVirtualThread(() -> {}) from JDK21. It seems good! Next, I should make sure to package things outside of any library packages, like the existing org_springframework_boot.spring_boot. Also, I need to create a one-to-one class file named ProcessInfoTest.java. I wonder if I should inspect the generated coverage stats—there might be dynamic reports to consider. That would help in evaluating the implementation!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_FLNOevP0stPbEw4zL4kX1yU1|fc_02c11d5e92f6616c016a24f91791908196b2bf3acfcf020811", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find tests/src/org.springframework.boot/spring-boot/4.0.6/build/nativ